      <div id="mmi-31186" class="title-module colspan-4 rag title-module--prominence-2 colspan-4 rag measurable magic-module" data-event-category="magic_module/title_module/31186" data-event-label="Title Module At Yale (9/77)" data-instance-id="31186" data-id="31454">                  
<h2 class="title-module__title page-title--prominence-2" aria-label="At Yale
">
        <span role="presentation" aria-hidden="true">At</span>
        <span role="presentation" aria-hidden="true">Yale</span>
</h2>


</div>


  <a name="mmi-44210"></a>
  



      <div id="mmi-44210" class="scrolling-text-module colspan-4 rag measurable magic-module" data-event-category="magic_module/scrolling_text_module/44210" data-event-label="Scrolling Text Module 44210 (10/77)" data-instance-id="44210" data-id="107928">                  <div class="scrolling-text-module__inner" style="max-height: 240.0em" tabindex="0">
    
    <span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Yale Pathways to Arts &amp; Humanities Summer Scholars<br>
Call for Enrichment Proposals 2025</strong></span><br>
<br>
The Yale Pathways to Arts &amp; Humanities Summer Scholars program is a free, 2-week, on-campus summer program offered to local public high school students. Yale faculty, graduate students, and staff are invited to design and teach a one-off, 60-min enrichment in our summer program. We are seeking proposals that will spark students’ imaginations and extend their learning beyond the walls of their high school classrooms.<br>
<br>
The number of students will depend on the format of the session and instructor preference. Instructors can teach the same enrichment multiple times with different groups of students. Enrichments happen alongside 5-day workshops – both weeks, Monday through Thursday.<br>
<br>
Program Dates<br>
   Week 1: July 21 - 25 <br>
   Week 2: July 28 - Aug 1<br>
Enrichment Timeslots<br>
   11:20 AM - 12:20 PM<br>
   Monday - Thursday<br>
<br>
A bit about the students: Yale Pathways to Arts &amp; Humanities Summer Scholars are a diverse group of students from New Haven, West Haven, and Orange public schools in grades 10 through 12. Approximately half would be the first in their family to go to college.<br>
<br>
<a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LxQq_sykpugk66RTpsw5aLUExDN9EO9Qto9DUvl-JAo/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.pegpxs7wt0ru" target="_blank">Full information &amp; how to submit &gt;</a>
</div>

